{"type":"message","id":"3da27879","parentId":"94eaeb36","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:13:10.687Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_9zcpyie8v6rk_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 101134\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze my current state and determine the next concrete action.\r\n\r\nCurrent status:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n- CFI Analysis is complete with findings about frequency-invariants\r\n- Next pending action: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe key finding from CFI analysis:\r\n- 44.8% of frequency-invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Need to compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline\r\n\r\nThis is the logical next step - implement the experiment that was flagged as \"Next\" in the CFI results. Let me design a concrete experiment that compares:\r\n1. Frequency baseline compression\r\n2. CFI-weighted compression\r\n\r\nI'll create an experiment script that:\r\n- Loads the frequency invariants from CFI_RESULTS.md or the raw data\r\n- Implements both compression strategies\r\n- Compares prediction quality\r\n\r\nLet me first check what data files exist from the CFI analysis to understand what I'm working with.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis revealed that 94.3% of frequency-invariants are noise (CFI<0.7), but we haven't yet tested whether filtering by CFI improves compression quality. The next pending action is the CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a compression comparison experiment script that tests CFI-weighted filtering against frequency baseline, measuring next-pulse prediction quality on actual pulse history data.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nFiltering frequency-invariants by CFI threshold will improve compression quality by removing metaprogramming artifacts (CFI=0) while preserving true causal anchors (CFI>0.7).\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-based Compression\r\n- Sort invariants by frequency (descending)\r\n- Select top-N by frequency\r\n- Measure reconstruction quality\r\n\r\n### Treatment: CFI-weighted Compression  \r\n- Sort invariants by CFI score (descending)\r\n- Select top-N by CFI threshold (e.g., CFI >= 0.7)\r\n- Measure reconstruction quality\r\n\r\n### Metric: Next-Pulse Prediction\r\n- Given compressed state at pulse T, predict pulse T+1 content\r\n- Measure overlap with actual pulse T+1\r\n\r\n## Data Sources\r\n- `research/pulse_history/` - all pulse_*.md files\r\n- `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` - invariant CFI scores\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted selection should achieve equal or better prediction with fewer invariants (higher compression ratio).\r\n\r\n---\r\nStatus: PENDING - awaiting implementation\r\nCreated: 2026-03-24\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:11:49\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774361590684}}
